3. Given a list of students sorted by marks, print the top 3 scorers.
-->Program
        import java.util.Arrays;
        import java.util.Comparator;
        import java.util.List;
        
        class Student {
        
            int id;
            String name;
            int marks;
        
            Student(int id, String name, int marks) {
                this.id = id;
                this.name = name;
                this.marks = marks;
            }
        }
        
        public class TopStudents {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
        
                List<Student> students = Arrays.asList(
                        new Student(101, "Ravi", 75),
                        new Student(102, "Anil", 95),
                        new Student(103, "Priya", 88),
                        new Student(104, "Rahul", 91),
                        new Student(105, "Kiran", 82)
                );
        
                students.stream()
                        .sorted(Comparator.comparingInt((Student s) -> s.marks).reversed())
                        .limit(3)
                        .forEach(s ->
                                System.out.println(s.name + " : " + s.marks));
            }
        }
        Output
            Anil : 95
            Rahul : 91
            Priya : 88






4. Find the second-highest salary using skip() and limit().
-->Program
        import java.util.Arrays;
        import java.util.Comparator;
        import java.util.List;
        
        class Employee {
        
            int id;
            String name;
            double salary;
        
            Employee(int id, String name, double salary) {
                this.id = id;
                this.name = name;
                this.salary = salary;
            }
        }
        
        public class SecondHighestSalary {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
        
                List<Employee> employees = Arrays.asList(
                        new Employee(101, "Ravi", 50000),
                        new Employee(102, "Anil", 75000),
                        new Employee(103, "Priya", 65000),
                        new Employee(104, "Rahul", 90000)
                );
        
                employees.stream()
                        .sorted(Comparator.comparingDouble((Employee e) -> e.salary).reversed())
                        .skip(1)
                        .limit(1)
                        .forEach(e ->
                                System.out.println(e.name + " : " + e.salary));
            }
        }
        Output
            Anil : 75000.0





Summary :
| Question              | Stream Methods Used                 | Purpose                        |
| --------------------- | ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------ |
| First 5 elements      | `limit(5)`                          | Returns first 5 elements       |
| Skip first 3 elements | `skip(3)`                           | Ignores first 3 elements       |
| Top 3 students        | `sorted()` + `limit(3)`             | Highest 3 marks                |
| Second-highest salary | `sorted()` + `skip(1)` + `limit(1)` | Gets the second highest salary |



Interview Tip
    limit()
    numbers.stream()
           .limit(3)
           .forEach(System.out::println);
    
    Output
    
    10
    20
    30
    skip()
    numbers.stream()
           .skip(3)
           .forEach(System.out::println);
    
    Output
    
    40
    50
    60
    70
    Using Both Together
    numbers.stream()
           .skip(2)
           .limit(3)
           .forEach(System.out::println);
    
    Input
    
    [10,20,30,40,50,60,70]
    
    Output
    
    30
    40
    50
    Frequently Asked Interview Examples
    // First 5 records
    stream.limit(5);
    
    // Skip first 10 records (pagination)
    stream.skip(10);
    
    // Get records 11 to 20
    stream.skip(10)
          .limit(10);
    
    // Second highest salary
    stream.sorted(Comparator.reverseOrder())
          .skip(1)
          .findFirst();
    
    limit() and skip() are commonly used for pagination, top-N queries, and ranking-related interview questions.
